Ammonia release emergency response would be done by the Salinas City Fire Department.  DCC~CDS has coordinated emergency response with the Fire Department including the installation of a Knox Box.  WPS would also be notified in case of a release.  WPS is located about 10 miles from the facility and employs technicians trained beyond 29 CFR 1910.120(q) Awareness level.  The Technician's role would be to support the Fire Department if an ammonia emergency occurs.  Ammonia emergency equipment is maintained under the control of WPS.  WPS maintains written ammonia emergency procedures.

1.6   Planned changes to improve safety

The primary mechanisms to identify and plan safety improvements include (but are not limited to):
 - Process Hazard Analysis revalidation/update;
 - Cal/ARP Seismic Assessment;
 - Compliance Audits;
 - Mechanical Integrity Program (Routine Inspections & Maintenance);
 - Triennial IIAR Bulletin 109 Inspections; and,
 - DCC~CDS & WPS Inspection Protocols

Each of the Programs above may result in recommendations ranging from capital improvements to routine maintenance of the plant.  When appropriate Service Calls are established in parallel to identified needs.  Current planned changes to improve safety include recent PHA 5-Year update recommendations, which includes mechanical and administrative improvements.  A written record of the recommendations has been prepared and submitted to DCC Management; some of which had been completed at the time this report was submitted.  Completion of all changes resulting from the PHA is expected by 2/20/2015, during seasonal shutdown.   

